

I believe people will gravitate towards a better health status if they are actively involved in health 
decision-making. The way forward is health service re-organisation as a path towards improving 
the link between health facilities and their communities. This pathway closely matches the 
components of this year’s sub-theme, Plurality and Partnerships. I envision a combination of 
strategies that can be steps towards attaining this goal. The core framework will be a community-
oriented primary care system, in association with a detailed patient follow-up model and private-
public collaboration.
The Community- Oriented Primary Care framework was initially imagined as the perfect junction 
between traditional clinical care and public health. It happens to be a key component in repairing 
the gap that has been created between health facilities and their communities. It will involve 
primarily defining and characterising the main community linked to each health facility. A work 
that will be accomplished by a network of community health workers, CHWs (presently in 
Cameroon, CHWs are sponsored by the WHO), through in-depth data collection (demographics, 
epidemiologic data, and qualitative data). Methods used will be surveys, focused group 
discussions, informant interviews and analysis of vital statistics. The next step will involve 
prioritising health problems in the community and developing targeted interventions (direct-
clinical care, enabling services and community-level interventions). This will be the basis of 
actions carried out in every department of a health facility.
The next component of this concept framework will be advocating for a dedicated patient follow-
up department as a priority in the establishment of facilities. Presently, the Ministry of Public 
Health acknowledges that the two main departments necessary in every health facility are a 
medical department and a nursing department. The efficacy of a dedicated patient follow-up 
department has been demonstrated so far in Uganda by Nawaggi, et al,2018, to improve patient 
linkage and retention, in Ivory Coast by the AMAFRICA project, 2015, through telephone calls to 
cancer patients, Zambia by Foloko M et al, 2024, for retention of HIV patients, the list goes on. 
With efficacy so evident, I would advocate for the vulgarization of such endeavours in Cameroon. 
Presently, I work in a private medical cabinet with a dedicated patient follow-up unit. I have seen 
first-hand what is necessary for the establishment of such a department in terms of human 
resources, logistics and finances. But such endeavours shouldn’t stay limited to the private sector. 
This brings me to my final point of public-private cooperation.
My professional experience so far has been both in a public health center and a private medical 
cabinet. This gave me an opportunity to duely appreciate the main differences areas in which 
communion between the public and the private sector will help strengthen the relationship between 
health facilities and their communities. Two main areas completely held by the public sector and 
almost entirely ignored by the private sector are immunization and the use of CHW. I will advocate 
for the adaptation of models of care with entry points being private clinics in this two categories. 